# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dwdm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] In fiber-optic communications, **wavelength-division multiplexing** (**WDM**) is a technology which multiplexes a number of optical carrier signals onto a single optical fiber by using different wavelengths (i.e., colors) of laser light.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] This technique enables bidirectional communications over a single strand of fiber (also called **wavelength-division duplexing**) as well as multiplication of capacity.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] The term WDM is commonly applied to an optical carrier, which is typically described by its wavelength, whereas frequency-division multiplexing typically applies to a radio carrier, more often described by frequency.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] This is purely conventional because wavelength and frequency communicate the same information.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Specifically, frequency (in Hertz, which is cycles per second) multiplied by wavelength (the physical length of one cycle) equals the velocity of the carrier wave.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] In a vacuum, this is the speed of light (usually denoted by the lowercase letter, c).
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] In glass fiber, velocity is substantially slower - usually about 0.7 times c.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] The data rate in practical systems is a fraction of the carrier frequency.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] A WDM system uses a multiplexer at the transmitter to join the several signals together and a demultiplexer at the receiver to split them apart.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] With the right type of fiber, it is possible to have a device that does both simultaneously and can function as an optical add-drop multiplexer.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] The optical filtering devices used have conventionally been etalons (stable solid-state single-frequency Fabry–Pérot interferometers in the form of thin-film-coated optical glass).
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] As there are three different WDM types, whereof one is called *WDM*, the notation *xWDM* is normally used when discussing the technology as such.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] The concept was first published in 1970 by Delange, and by 1980 WDM systems were being realized in the laboratory.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] The first WDM systems combined only two signals.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Modern systems can handle 160 signals and can thus expand a basic 100 Gbit/s system over a single fiber pair to over 16 Tbit/s.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM systems are popular with telecommunications companies because they allow them to expand the capacity of the network without laying more fiber.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] By using WDM and optical amplifiers, they can accommodate several generations of technology development in their optical infrastructure without having to overhaul the backbone network.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] The capacity of a given link can be expanded simply by upgrading the multiplexers and demultiplexers at each end.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] This is often done by the use of optical-to-electrical-to-optical (O/E/O) translation at the very edge of the transport network, thus permitting interoperation with existing equipment with optical interfaces.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Most WDM systems operate on single-mode optical fiber cables which have a core diameter of 9 μm.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Certain forms of WDM can also be used in multi-mode optical fiber cables (also known as premises cables) which have core diameters of 50 or 62.5 μm.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Early WDM systems were expensive and complicated to run.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] However, recent standardization and a better understanding of the dynamics of WDM systems have made WDM less expensive to deploy.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Optical receivers, in contrast to laser sources, tend to be wideband devices.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Therefore, the demultiplexer must provide the wavelength selectivity of the receiver in the WDM system.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM systems are divided into three different wavelength patterns: **normal** (WDM), **coarse** (CWDM) and **dense** (DWDM).
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Normal WDM (sometimes called BWDM) uses the two normal wavelengths 1310 and 1550 nm on one fiber.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Coarse WDM provides up to 16 channels across multiple transmission windows of silica fibers.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] *Dense WDM* (DWDM) uses the C-Band (1530 nm-1565 nm) transmission window but with denser channel spacing.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Channel plans vary, but a typical DWDM system would use 40 channels at 100 GHz spacing or 80 channels with 50 GHz spacing.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Some technologies are capable of 12.5 GHz spacing (sometimes called ultra-dense WDM).
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] New amplification options (Raman amplification) enable the extension of the usable wavelengths to the L-band (1565–1625 nm), more or less doubling these numbers.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Coarse wavelength-division multiplexing (CWDM), in contrast to DWDM, uses increased channel spacing to allow less sophisticated and thus cheaper transceiver designs.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] To provide 16 channels on a single fiber, CWDM uses the entire frequency band spanning the second and third transmission windows (1310/1550 nm respectively) including the critical frequencies where OH scattering may occur.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] OH-free silica fibers are recommended if the wavelengths between the second and third transmission windows are to be used.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Avoiding this region, the channels 47, 49, 51, 53, 55, 57, 59, 61 remain and these are the most commonly used.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] With OS2 fibers the water peak problem is overcome, and all possible 18 channels can be used.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM, CWDM and DWDM are based on the same concept of using multiple wavelengths of light on a single fiber but differ in the spacing of the wavelengths, number of channels, and the ability to amplify the multiplexed signals in the optical space.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Erbium-doped optical fiber amplifiers (EDFAs) provide an efficient wideband amplification for the C-band, Raman amplification adds a mechanism for amplification in the L-band.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] For CWDM, wideband optical amplification is not available, limiting the optical spans to several tens of kilometers.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Originally, the term *coarse wavelength-division multiplexing* (CWDM) was fairly generic and described a number of different channel configurations.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] In general, the choice of channel spacings and frequency in these configurations precluded the use of EDFAs.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Prior to the relatively recent ITU standardization of the term, one common definition for CWDM was two or more signals multiplexed onto a single fiber, with one signal in the 1550 nm band and the other in the 1310 nm band.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] In 2002, the ITU standardized a channel spacing grid for CWDM (ITU-T G.694.2) using the wavelengths from 1270 nm through 1610 nm with a channel spacing of 20 nm.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] ITU G.694.2 was revised in 2003 to shift the channel centers by 1 nm so, strictly speaking, the center wavelengths are 1271 to 1611 nm.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Many CWDM wavelengths below 1470 nm are considered unusable on older G.652 specification fibers, due to the increased attenuation in the 1270–1470 nm bands.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Newer fibers which conform to the G.652.C and G.652.D standards, such as Corning SMF-28e and Samsung Widepass, nearly eliminate the water-related attenuation peak at 1383 nm and allow for full operation of all 18 ITU CWDM channels in metropolitan networks.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] The main characteristic of the recent ITU CWDM standard is that the signals are not spaced appropriately for amplification by EDFAs.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] This limits the total CWDM optical span to somewhere near 60 km for a 2.5 Gbit/s signal, suitable for use in metropolitan applications.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] The relaxed optical frequency stabilization requirements allow the associated costs of CWDM to approach those of non-WDM optical components.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] CWDM is being used in cable television networks, where different wavelengths are used for the *downstream* and *upstream* signals.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] In these systems, the wavelengths used are often widely separated.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] For example, the downstream signal might be at 1310 nm while the upstream signal is at 1550 nm.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] The 10GBASE-LX4 10 Gbit/s physical layer standard is an example of a CWDM system in which four wavelengths near 1310 nm, each carrying a 3.125 Gbit/s data stream, are used to carry 10 Gbit/s of aggregate data.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Passive CWDM is an implementation of CWDM that uses no electrical power.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] It separates the wavelengths using passive optical components such as bandpass filters and prisms.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Many manufacturers are promoting passive CWDM to deploy fiber to the home.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] An **intermediate line repeater** is placed approximately every 80–100 km to compensate for the loss of optical power as the signal travels along the fiber.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] The 'multi-wavelength optical signal' is amplified by an EDFA, which usually consists of several amplifier stages.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] An **intermediate optical terminal**, or **optical add-drop multiplexer (OADM)**.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] This is a remote amplification site that amplifies the multi-wavelength signal that may have traversed up to 140 km or more before reaching the remote site.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Optical diagnostics and telemetry are often extracted or inserted at such a site to allow for localization of any fiber breaks or signal impairments.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] In more sophisticated systems (which are no longer point-to-point), several signals out of the multi-wavelength optical signal may be removed and dropped locally.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] At the remote site, the terminal de-multiplexer consisting of an optical de-multiplexer and one or more wavelength-converting transponders separates the multi-wavelength optical signal back into individual data signals and outputs them on separate fibers for client-layer systems (such as SONET/SDH).
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Originally, this de-multiplexing was performed entirely passively, except for some telemetry, as most SONET systems can receive 1,550 nm signals.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] However, in order to allow for transmission to remote client-layer systems (and to allow for digital domain signal integrity determination) such de-multiplexed signals are usually sent to O/E/O output transponders prior to being relayed to their client-layer systems.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Often, the functionality of the output transponder has been integrated into that of the input transponder, so that most commercial systems have transponders that support bi-directional interfaces on both their 1,550 nm (i.e., internal) side, and external (i.e., client-facing) side.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Transponders in some systems supporting 40 GHz nominal operation may also perform forward error correction (FEC) via digital wrapper technology, as described in the ITU-T G.709 standard.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] This is data channel that uses an additional wavelength usually outside the EDFA amplification band (at 1,510 nm, 1,620 nm, 1,310 nm or another proprietary wavelength).
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] The OSC carries information about the multi-wavelength optical signal as well as remote conditions at the optical terminal or EDFA site.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] It is also normally used for remote software upgrades and user (i.e., network operator) Network Management information.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] It is the multi-wavelength analog to SONET's DCC (or supervisory channel).
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] ITU standards suggest that the OSC should utilize an OC-3 signal structure, though some vendors have opted to use Fast Ethernet or another signal format.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Unlike the 1550 nm multi-wavelength signal containing client data, the OSC is always terminated at intermediate amplifier sites, where it receives local information before re-transmission.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] The introduction of the ITU-T G.694.1 frequency grid in 2002 has made it easier to integrate WDM with older but more standard SONET/SDH systems.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM wavelengths are positioned in a grid having exactly 100 GHz (about 0.8 nm) spacing in optical frequency, with a reference frequency fixed at 193.10 THz (1,552.52 nm).
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] The main grid is placed inside the optical fiber amplifier bandwidth, but can be extended to wider bandwidths.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] The first commercial deployment of DWDM was made by Ciena Corporation on the Sprint network in June 1996.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Today's DWDM systems use 50 GHz or even 25 GHz channel spacing for up to 160 channel operation.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] DWDM systems have to maintain more stable wavelength or frequency than those needed for CWDM because of the closer spacing of the wavelengths.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Precision temperature control of the laser transmitter is required in DWDM systems to prevent drift off a very narrow frequency window of the order of a few GHz.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] These factors of smaller volume and higher performance result in DWDM systems typically being more expensive than CWDM.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Recent innovations in DWDM transport systems include pluggable and software-tunable transceiver modules capable of operating on 40 or 80 channels.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] This dramatically reduces the need for discrete spare pluggable modules, when a handful of pluggable devices can handle the full range of wavelengths.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Wavelength-converting transponders originally translated the transmit wavelength of a client-layer signal into one of the DWDM system's internal wavelengths in the 1,550 nm band.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] External wavelengths in the 1,550 nm most likely need to be translated, as they almost certainly do not have the required frequency stability tolerances nor the optical power necessary for the system's EDFA.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] In the mid-1990s, however, wavelength-converting transponders rapidly took on the additional function of signal regeneration.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Signal regeneration in transponders quickly evolved through 1R to 2R to 3R and into overhead-monitoring multi-bitrate 3R regenerators.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] of the received optical signal, with little signal cleanup occurring.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] This limited the reach of early DWDM systems because the signal had to be handed off to a client-layer receiver (likely from a different vendor) before the signal deteriorated too far.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Signal monitoring was basically confined to optical domain parameters such as received power.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Some rudimentary signal-quality monitoring was done by such transmitters that basically looked at analogue parameters.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] 3R Transponders were fully digital and normally able to view SONET/SDH section layer overhead bytes such as A1 and A2 to determine signal quality health.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] transponders, which will normally mean the transponder is able to perform 3R regeneration on OC-3/12/48 signals, and possibly gigabit Ethernet, and reporting on signal health by monitoring SONET/SDH section layer overhead bytes.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Many transponders will be able to perform full multi-rate 3R in both directions.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] transponders, which will perform Section layer overhead monitoring to all rates up to and including OC-192.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] (from multiplexed transponder) has different names depending on vendor.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] For DWDM the range between C21-C60 is the most common range, for Mux/Demux in 8, 16, 40 or 96 sizes.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] As mentioned above, intermediate optical amplification sites in DWDM systems may allow for the dropping and adding of certain wavelength channels.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] In most systems deployed as of August 2006 this is done infrequently, because adding or dropping wavelengths requires manually inserting or replacing wavelength-selective cards.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] This is costly, and in some systems requires that all active traffic be removed from the DWDM system because inserting or removing the wavelength-specific cards interrupts the multi-wavelength optical signal.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] With a ROADM, network operators can remotely reconfigure the multiplexer by sending soft commands.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] The architecture of the ROADM is such that dropping or adding wavelengths does not interrupt the *pass-through* channels.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Numerous technological approaches are utilized for various commercial ROADMs, the tradeoff being between cost, optical power, and flexibility.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] When the network topology is a mesh, where nodes are interconnected by fibers to form an arbitrary graph, an additional fiber interconnection device is needed to route the signals from an input port to the desired output port.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] These devices are called optical crossconnectors (OXCs).
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Various categories of OXCs include electronic ("opaque"), optical ("transparent"), and wavelength-selective devices.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Cisco's Enhanced WDM system is a network architecture that combines two different types of multiplexing technologies to transmit data over optical fibers.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] EWDM combines 1 Gbit/s Coarse Wave Division Multiplexing (CWDM) connections using SFPs and GBICs with 10 Gbit/s Dense Wave Division Multiplexing (DWDM) connections using XENPAK, X2 or XFP DWDM modules.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] The Enhanced WDM system can use either passive or boosted DWDM connections to allow a longer range for the connection.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] In addition to this, C form-factor pluggable modules deliver 100 Gbit/s Ethernet suitable for high-speed Internet backbone connections.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Shortwave WDM uses vertical-cavity surface-emitting laser (VCSEL) transceivers with four wavelengths in the 846 to 953 nm range over a single OM5 fiber, or two-fiber connectivity for OM3/OM4 fiber.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] ) communication, two wavelengths will be required if on the same fiber; if separate fibers are used in a so-called fiber pair, then the same wavelength is normally used and it is not WDM.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] As a result, at each end both a transmitter and a receiver will be required.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] A combination of a transmitter and a receiver is called a transceiver; it converts an electrical signal to and from an optical signal.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM transceivers made for single-strand operation require the opposing transmitters to use different wavelengths.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] WDM transceivers additionally require an optical splitter/combiner to couple the transmitter and receiver paths onto the one fiber strand.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] This means that in effect wavelength converters are needed instead, which is exactly what a transponder is.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] nm optical signal to/from an electrical signal, and the second transceiver converting the electrical signal to/from an optical signal at the required wavelength.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] Transponders that don't use an intermediate electrical signal (all-optical transponders) are in development.
[src:dwdm/dense-wavelength-division-multiplexing] See also transponders (optical communications) for different functional views on the meaning of optical transponders.
[src:dwdm/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] An **optical add-drop multiplexer** (**OADM**) is a device used in wavelength-division multiplexing (WDM) systems for multiplexing and routing different channels of light into or out of a single-mode fiber (SMF).
[src:dwdm/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] This is a type of optical node, which is generally used for the formation and the construction of optical telecommunications networks.
[src:dwdm/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] "Add" and "drop" here refer to the capability of the device to add one or more new wavelength channels to an existing multi-wavelength WDM signal, and/or to drop (remove) one or more channels, passing those signals to another network path.
[src:dwdm/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] An OADM may be considered to be a specific type of optical cross-connect.
[src:dwdm/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] A traditional OADM consists of three stages: an optical demultiplexer, an optical multiplexer, and between them a method of reconfiguring the paths between the demultiplexer, the multiplexer and a set of ports for adding and dropping signals.
[src:dwdm/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] The demultiplexer separates wavelengths in an input fiber onto ports.
[src:dwdm/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] The reconfiguration can be achieved by a fiber patch panel or by optical switches which direct the wavelengths to the multiplexer or to drop ports.
[src:dwdm/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] The multiplexer multiplexes the wavelength channels that are to continue on from demultiplexer ports with those from the add ports, onto a single output fiber.
[src:dwdm/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] All the lightpaths that directly pass an OADM are termed *cut-through lightpaths*, while those that are added or dropped at the OADM node are termed *added/dropped lightpaths*.
[src:dwdm/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] An OADM with remotely reconfigurable optical switches (for example 1×2) in the middle stage is called a reconfigurable OADM (ROADM).
[src:dwdm/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] Ones without this feature are known as *fixed* OADMs.
[src:dwdm/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] While the term OADM applies to both types, it is often used interchangeably with ROADM.
[src:dwdm/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] Physically, there are several ways to make an OADM.
[src:dwdm/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] There are a variety of demultiplexer and multiplexer technologies including thin film filters, fiber Bragg gratings with optical circulators, free space grating devices and integrated planar arrayed waveguide gratings.
[src:dwdm/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] The switching or reconfiguration functions range from the manual fiber patch panel to a variety of switching technologies including microelectromechanical systems (MEMS), liquid crystal and thermo-optic switches in planar waveguide circuits.
[src:dwdm/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] Although both have add/drop functionality, OADMs are distinct from add-drop multiplexers.
[src:dwdm/optical-add-drop-multiplexer] The former function in the photonic domain under wavelength-division multiplexing, while the latter are implicitly considered to function in the traditional SONET/SDH networks.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] An **optical amplifier** is a device that amplifies an optical signal directly, without the need to first convert it to an electrical signal.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] An optical amplifier may be thought of as a laser without an optical cavity, or one in which feedback from the cavity is suppressed.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Optical amplifiers are important in optical communication and laser physics.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] They are used as optical repeaters in the long distance fiber-optic cables which carry much of the world's telecommunication links.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] There are several different physical mechanisms that can be used to amplify a light signal, which correspond to the major types of optical amplifiers.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] In doped fiber amplifiers and bulk lasers, stimulated emission in the amplifier's gain medium causes amplification of incoming light.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] In semiconductor optical amplifiers (SOAs), electron–hole recombination occurs.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] In Raman amplifiers, Raman scattering of incoming light with phonons in the lattice of the gain medium produces photons coherent with the incoming photons.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Parametric amplifiers use parametric amplification.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The principle of optical amplification was invented by Gordon Gould on November 13, 1957.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] He filed US Patent US80453959A on April 6, 1959, titled "Light Amplifiers Employing Collisions to Produce Population Inversions" (subsequently amended as a continuation in part and finally issued as U.S. patent 4,746,201A on May 4, 1988).
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The patent covered “the amplification of light by the stimulated emission of photons from ions, atoms or molecules in gaseous, liquid or solid state.” In total, Gould obtained 48 patents related to the optical amplifier that covered 80% of the lasers on the market at the time of issuance.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Gould co-founded an optical telecommunications equipment firm, Optelecom Inc., that helped start Ciena Corp with his former head of Light Optics Research, David Huber and Kevin Kimberlin.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Huber and Steve Alexander of Ciena invented the dual-stage optical amplifier (U.S. patent 5,159,601) that was a key to the first dense wave division multiplexing (DWDM) system, that they released in June 1996.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] This marked the start of optical networking.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Optical amplification WDM systems are the common basis of all local, metro, national, intercontinental and subsea telecommunications networks and the technology of choice for the fiber optic backbones of the Internet (e.g. fiber-optic cables form a basis of modern-day computer networking).
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Almost any laser active gain medium can be pumped to produce gain for light at the wavelength of a laser made with the same material as its gain medium.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Such amplifiers are commonly used to produce high power laser systems.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Special types such as regenerative amplifiers and chirped-pulse amplifiers are used to amplify ultrashort pulses.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Amplification is achieved by stimulated emission of photons from dopant ions in the doped fiber.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The pump laser excites ions into a higher energy from where they can decay via stimulated emission of a photon at the signal wavelength back to a lower energy level.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The excited ions can also decay spontaneously (spontaneous emission) or even through nonradiative processes involving interactions with phonons of the glass matrix.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] These last two decay mechanisms compete with stimulated emission reducing the efficiency of light amplification.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The *amplification window* of an optical amplifier is the range of optical wavelengths for which the amplifier yields a usable gain.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The amplification window is determined by the spectroscopic properties of the dopant ions, the glass structure of the optical fiber, and the wavelength and power of the pump laser.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Although the electronic transitions of an isolated ion are very well defined, broadening of the energy levels occurs when the ions are incorporated into the glass of the optical fiber and thus the amplification window is also broadened.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] This broadening is both homogeneous (all ions exhibit the same broadened spectrum) and inhomogeneous (different ions in different glass locations exhibit different spectra).
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Homogeneous broadening arises from the interactions with phonons of the glass, while inhomogeneous broadening is caused by differences in the glass sites where different ions are hosted.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Different sites expose ions to different local electric fields, which shifts the energy levels via the Stark effect.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] In addition, the Stark effect also removes the degeneracy of energy states having the same total angular momentum (specified by the quantum number J).
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Thus, for example, the trivalent erbium ion (Er3+) has a ground state with J = 15/2, and in the presence of an electric field splits into J + 1/2 = 8 sublevels with slightly different energies.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The first excited state has J = 13/2 and therefore a Stark manifold with 7 sublevels.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Transitions from the J = 13/2 excited state to the J= 15/2 ground state are responsible for the gain at 1500 nm wavelength.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The gain spectrum of the EDFA has several peaks that are smeared by the above broadening mechanisms.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The net result is a very broad spectrum (30 nm in silica, typically).
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The broad gain-bandwidth of fiber amplifiers make them particularly useful in wavelength-division multiplexed communications systems as a single amplifier can be utilized to amplify all signals being carried on a fiber and whose wavelengths fall within the gain window.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] An *erbium-doped waveguide amplifier* (EDWA) is an optical amplifier that uses a waveguide to boost an optical signal.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] A relatively high-powered beam of light known as the pump light is mixed with the amplified input signal using a coupler.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The input signal and the pump light must be at significantly different wavelengths.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The mixed light is guided into a section of fiber with erbium ions included in the core.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] This high-powered light beam excites the erbium ions to their higher-energy state.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] When the photons belonging to the signal at a different wavelength from the pump light meet the excited erbium ions, the erbium ions undergo stimulated emission and return to their lower-energy state.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] A significant point is that the erbium gives up its energy in the form of additional photons which are exactly in the same phase, frequency, and direction as the signal being amplified.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] So the signal is amplified along its direction of travel only.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] This is not unusual – when an atom "lases" it always gives up its energy in the same direction and phase as the incoming light.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Thus all of the additional signal power is guided in the same fiber mode as the incoming signal.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The pump light can be sent into the fiber in the same direction (forward pumping) or opposite direction of the signal (backwards pumping).
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] An optical isolator is usually placed at the output to prevent reflections returning from the attached fiber.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Such reflections disrupt amplifier operation and in the extreme case can cause the amplifier to become a laser.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The erbium doped amplifier is a high gain amplifier.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The principal source of noise in DFAs is amplified spontaneous emission (ASE), which has a spectrum approximately the same as the gain spectrum of the amplifier.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Noise figure in an ideal DFA is 3 dB, while practical amplifiers can have noise figure as large as 6–8 dB.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] As well as decaying via stimulated emission, electrons in the upper energy level can also decay by spontaneous emission, which occurs at random, depending upon the glass structure and inversion level.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Photons are emitted spontaneously in all directions, but a proportion of those will be emitted in a direction that falls within the numerical aperture of the fiber and are thus captured and guided by the fiber.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Those photons captured may then interact with other dopant ions, and are thus amplified by stimulated emission.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The initial spontaneous emission is therefore amplified in the same manner as the signals, hence the term a*mplified spontaneous emission*.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] ASE is emitted by the amplifier in both the forward and reverse directions, but only the forward ASE is a direct concern to system performance since that noise will co-propagate with the signal to the receiver where it degrades system performance.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Counter-propagating ASE can, however, lead to degradation of the amplifier's performance since the ASE can deplete the inversion level and thereby reduce the gain of the amplifier and increase the noise produced relative to the desired signal gain.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Noise figure can be analyzed in both the optical domain and in the electrical domain.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] In the optical domain, measurement of the ASE, the optical signal gain, and signal wavelength using an optical spectrum analyzer permits calculation of the noise figure.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] For the electrical measurement method, the detected photocurrent noise is evaluated with a low-noise electrical spectrum analyzer, which along with measurement of the amplifier gain permits a noise figure measurement.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Generally, the optical technique provides a more simple method, though it is not inclusive of excess noise effects captured by the electrical method such multi-path interference (MPI) noise generation.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] In both methods, attention to effects such as the spontaneous emission accompanying the input signal are critical to accurate measurement of noise figure.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Gain is achieved in a DFA due to population inversion of the dopant ions.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The inversion level of a DFA is set, primarily, by the power of the pump wavelength and the power at the amplified wavelengths.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] As the signal power increases, or the pump power decreases, the inversion level will reduce and thereby the gain of the amplifier will be reduced.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] This effect is known as gain saturation – as the signal level increases, the amplifier saturates and cannot produce any more output power, and therefore the gain reduces.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Saturation is also commonly known as gain compression.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] To achieve optimum noise performance DFAs are operated under a significant amount of gain compression (10 dB typically), since that reduces the rate of spontaneous emission, thereby reducing ASE.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Another advantage of operating the DFA in the gain saturation region is that small fluctuations in the input signal power are reduced in the output amplified signal: smaller input signal powers experience larger (less saturated) gain, while larger input powers see less gain.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The leading edge of the pulse is amplified, until the saturation energy of the gain medium is reached.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] In some condition, the width (FWHM) of the pulse is reduced.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Due to the inhomogeneous portion of the linewidth broadening of the dopant ions, the gain spectrum has an inhomogeneous component and gain saturation occurs, to a small extent, in an inhomogeneous manner.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] This effect is known as *spectral hole burning* because a high power signal at one wavelength can 'burn' a hole in the gain for wavelengths close to that signal by saturation of the inhomogeneously broadened ions.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Spectral holes vary in width depending on the characteristics of the optical fiber in question and the power of the burning signal, but are typically less than 1 nm at the short wavelength end of the C-band, and a few nm at the long wavelength end of the C-band.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The depth of the holes are very small, though, making it difficult to observe in practice.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Although the DFA is essentially a polarization independent amplifier, a small proportion of the dopant ions interact preferentially with certain polarizations and a small dependence on the polarization of the input signal may occur (typically < 0.5 dB).
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] This is called polarization dependent gain (PDG).
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The absorption and emission cross sections of the ions can be modeled as ellipsoids with the major axes aligned at random in all directions in different glass sites.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The random distribution of the orientation of the ellipsoids in a glass produces a macroscopically isotropic medium, but a strong pump laser induces an anisotropic distribution by selectively exciting those ions that are more aligned with the optical field vector of the pump.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Also, those excited ions aligned with the signal field produce more stimulated emission.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The change in gain is thus dependent on the alignment of the polarizations of the pump and signal lasers – i.e. whether the two lasers are interacting with the same sub-set of dopant ions or not.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] In an ideal doped fiber without birefringence, the PDG would be inconveniently large.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Fortunately, in optical fibers small amounts of birefringence are always present and, furthermore, the fast and slow axes vary randomly along the fiber length.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] A typical DFA has several tens of meters, long enough to already show this randomness of the birefringence axes.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] These two combined effects (which in transmission fibers give rise to polarization mode dispersion) produce a misalignment of the relative polarizations of the signal and pump lasers along the fiber, thus tending to average out the PDG.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The result is that PDG is very difficult to observe in a single amplifier (but is noticeable in links with several cascaded amplifiers).
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The erbium-doped fiber amplifier (EDFA) is the most deployed fiber amplifier as its amplification window coincides with the third transmission window of silica-based optical fiber.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The core of a silica fiber is doped with trivalent erbium ions (Er3+) and can be efficiently pumped with a laser at or near wavelengths of 980 nm and 1480 nm, and gain is exhibited in the 1550 nm region.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The EDFA amplification region varies from application to application and can be anywhere from a few nm up to ~80 nm.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Typical use of EDFA in telecommunications calls for *Conventional*, or C-band amplifiers (from ~1525 nm to ~1565 nm) or *Long*, or L-band amplifiers (from ~1565 nm to ~1610 nm).
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Both of these bands can be amplified by EDFAs, but it is normal to use two different amplifiers, each optimized for one of the bands.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The principal difference between C- and L-band amplifiers is that a longer length of doped fiber is used in L-band amplifiers.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The longer length of fiber allows a lower inversion level to be used, thereby giving emission at longer wavelengths (due to the band-structure of Erbium in silica) while still providing a useful amount of gain.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] EDFAs have two commonly used pumping bands – 980 nm and 1480 nm.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The 980 nm band has a higher absorption cross-section and is generally used where low-noise performance is required.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The absorption band is relatively narrow and so wavelength stabilised laser sources are typically needed.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The 1480 nm band has a lower, but broader, absorption cross-section and is generally used for higher power amplifiers.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] A combination of 980 nm and 1480 nm pumping is generally utilised in amplifiers.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Gain and lasing in erbium-doped fibers were first demonstrated in 1986–87 by two groups; one including David N.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Reekie, from the University of Southampton and one from AT&T Bell Laboratories, consisting of E.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The dual-stage optical amplifier which enabled dense wave division multiplexing (DWDM) was invented by Stephen B.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Thulium doped fiber amplifiers have been used in the S-band (1450–1490 nm) and Praseodymium doped amplifiers in the 1300 nm region.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] However, those regions have not seen any significant commercial use so far and so those amplifiers have not been the subject of as much development as the EDFA.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] However, Ytterbium doped fiber lasers and amplifiers, operating near 1 micrometre wavelength, have many applications in industrial processing of materials, as these devices can be made with extremely high output power (tens of kilowatts).
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Semiconductor optical amplifiers (SOAs) are amplifiers which use a semiconductor to provide the gain medium.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] These amplifiers have a similar structure to Fabry–Pérot laser diodes but with anti-reflection design elements at the end faces.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Recent designs include anti-reflective coatings and tilted wave guide and window regions which can reduce end face reflection to less than 0.001%.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Since this creates a loss of power from the cavity which is greater than the gain, it prevents the amplifier from acting as a laser.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Another type of SOA consists of two regions.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] One part has a structure of a Fabry-Pérot laser diode and the other has a tapered geometry in order to reduce the power density on the output facet.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Semiconductor optical amplifiers are typically made from group III-V compound semiconductors such as GaAs/AlGaAs, InP/InGaAs, InP/InGaAsP and InP/InAlGaAs, though any direct band gap semiconductors such as II-VI could conceivably be used.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Such amplifiers are often used in telecommunication systems in the form of fiber-pigtailed components, operating at signal wavelengths between 850 nm and 1600 nm and generating gains of up to 30 dB.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The semiconductor optical amplifier is of small size and electrically pumped.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] It can be potentially less expensive than the EDFA and can be integrated with semiconductor lasers, modulators, etc.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] However, the performance is still not comparable with the EDFA.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The SOA has higher noise, lower gain, moderate polarization dependence and high nonlinearity with fast transient time.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The main advantage of SOA is that all four types of nonlinear operations (cross gain modulation, cross phase modulation, wavelength conversion and four wave mixing) can be conducted.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Furthermore, SOA can be run with a low power laser.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] This originates from the short nanosecond or less upper state lifetime, so that the gain reacts rapidly to changes of pump or signal power and the changes of gain also cause phase changes which can distort the signals.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] This nonlinearity presents the most severe problem for optical communication applications.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] However it provides the possibility for gain in different wavelength regions from the EDFA.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] "Linear optical amplifiers" using gain-clamping techniques have been developed.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] High optical nonlinearity makes semiconductor amplifiers attractive for all optical signal processing like all-optical switching and wavelength conversion.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] There has been much research on semiconductor optical amplifiers as elements for optical signal processing, wavelength conversion, clock recovery, signal demultiplexing, and pattern recognition.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] A recent addition to the SOA family is the vertical-cavity SOA (VCSOA).
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] These devices are similar in structure to, and share many features with, vertical-cavity surface-emitting lasers (VCSELs).
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The major difference when comparing VCSOAs and VCSELs is the reduced mirror reflectivity used in the amplifier cavity.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] With VCSOAs, reduced feedback is necessary to prevent the device from reaching lasing threshold.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Due to the extremely short cavity length, and correspondingly thin gain medium, these devices exhibit very low single-pass gain (typically on the order of a few percent) and also a very large free spectral range (FSR).
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The small single-pass gain requires relatively high mirror reflectivity to boost the total signal gain.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] In addition to boosting the total signal gain, the use of the resonant cavity structure results in a very narrow gain bandwidth; coupled with the large FSR of the optical cavity, this effectively limits operation of the VCSOA to single-channel amplification.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Thus, VCSOAs can be seen as amplifying filters.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Given their vertical-cavity geometry, VCSOAs are resonant cavity optical amplifiers that operate with the input/output signal entering/exiting normal to the wafer surface.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] In addition to their small size, the surface normal operation of VCSOAs leads to a number of advantages, including low power consumption, low noise figure, polarization insensitive gain, and the ability to fabricate high fill factor two-dimensional arrays on a single semiconductor chip.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] These devices are still in the early stages of research, though promising preamplifier results have been demonstrated.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Further extensions to VCSOA technology are the demonstration of wavelength tunable devices.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] These MEMS-tunable vertical-cavity SOAs utilize a microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) based tuning mechanism for wide and continuous tuning of the peak gain wavelength of the amplifier.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] SOAs have a more rapid gain response, which is in the order of 1 to 100 ps.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] For high output power and broader wavelength range, tapered amplifiers are used.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] These amplifiers consist of a lateral single-mode section and a section with a tapered structure, where the laser light is amplified.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The tapered structure leads to a reduction of the power density at the output facet.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] In a Raman amplifier, the signal is intensified by Raman amplification.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Unlike the EDFA and SOA the amplification effect is achieved by a nonlinear interaction between the signal and a pump laser within an optical fiber.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] There are two types of Raman amplifier: distributed and lumped.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] A distributed Raman amplifier is one in which the transmission fiber is utilised as the gain medium by multiplexing a pump wavelength with signal wavelength, while a lumped Raman amplifier utilises a dedicated, shorter length of fiber to provide amplification.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] In the case of a lumped Raman amplifier, a highly nonlinear fiber with a small core is utilised to increase the interaction between signal and pump wavelengths, and thereby reduce the length of fiber required.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The pump light may be coupled into the transmission fiber in the same direction as the signal (co-directional pumping), in the opposite direction (contra-directional pumping) or both.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Contra-directional pumping is more common as the transfer of noise from the pump to the signal is reduced.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The pump power required for Raman amplification is higher than that required by the EDFA, with in excess of 500 mW being required to achieve useful levels of gain in a distributed amplifier.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Lumped amplifiers, where the pump light can be safely contained to avoid safety implications of high optical powers, may use over 1 W of optical power.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The principal advantage of Raman amplification is its ability to provide distributed amplification within the transmission fiber, thereby increasing the length of spans between amplifier and regeneration sites.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] The amplification bandwidth of Raman amplifiers is defined by the pump wavelengths utilised and so amplification can be provided over wider, and different, regions than may be possible with other amplifier types which rely on dopants and device design to define the amplification 'window'.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Raman amplifiers have some fundamental advantages.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] First, Raman gain exists in every fiber, which provides a cost-effective means of upgrading from the terminal ends.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Second, the gain is nonresonant, which means that gain is available over the entire transparency region of the fiber ranging from approximately 0.3 to 2 μm.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] A third advantage of Raman amplifiers is that the gain spectrum can be tailored by adjusting the pump wavelengths.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] For instance, multiple pump lines can be used to increase the optical bandwidth, and the pump distribution determines the gain flatness.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Another advantage of Raman amplification is that it is a relatively broad-band amplifier with a bandwidth > 5 THz, and the gain is reasonably flat over a wide wavelength range.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] However, a number of challenges for Raman amplifiers prevented their earlier adoption.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] First, compared to the EDFAs, Raman amplifiers have relatively poor pumping efficiency at lower signal powers.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Although a disadvantage, this lack of pump efficiency also makes gain clamping easier in Raman amplifiers.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Second, Raman amplifiers require a longer gain fiber.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] However, this disadvantage can be mitigated by combining gain and the dispersion compensation in a single fiber.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] A third disadvantage of Raman amplifiers is a fast response time, which gives rise to new sources of noise, as further discussed below.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Finally, there are concerns of nonlinear penalty in the amplifier for the WDM signal channels.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] An optical parametric amplifier allows the amplification of a weak signal-impulse in a nonlinear medium such as a noncentrosymmetric nonlinear medium (e.g.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Beta barium borate (BBO)) or even a standard fused silica optical fiber via the Kerr effect.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] In contrast to the previously mentioned amplifiers, which are mostly used in telecommunication environments, this type finds its main application in expanding the frequency tunability of ultrafast solid-state lasers (e.g.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] By using a noncollinear interaction geometry optical parametric amplifiers are capable of extremely broad amplification bandwidths.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] In the 21st century high power fiber lasers were adopted as an industrial material processing tool, and were expanding into other markets including the medical and scientific markets.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] One key enhancement enabling penetration into the scientific market was improvement in high finesse fiber amplifiers, which became able to deliver single frequency linewidths (<5 kHz) together with excellent beam quality and stable linearly polarized output.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Systems meeting these specifications steadily progressed from a few watts of output power initially, to tens of watts and later hundreds of watts.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] As of 2015 high finesse, high power and pulsed fiber amplifiers delivered power levels exceeding those available from commercial solid-state single-frequency sources, and stable optimized performance, opening up new scientific applications.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] There are several simulation tools that can be used to design optical amplifiers.
[src:dwdm/optical-amplifier] Popular commercial tools have been developed by Optiwave Systems and VPI Systems.
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] An **optical transport network** (**OTN**) is a digital wrapper that encapsulates frames of data, to allow multiple data sources to be sent on the same channel.
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] This creates an optical virtual private network for each client signal.
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] ITU-T defines an optical transport network as a set of optical network elements (ONE) connected by optical fiber links, able to provide functionality of transport, multiplexing, switching, management, supervision and survivability of optical channels carrying client signals.
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] An ONE may re-time, re-Amplify, re-shape (3R) but it does not have to be 3R – it can be purely photonic.
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] Unless connected by optical fibre links, it shall not be OTN.
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] Mere functionality of switching, management, supervision shall not make it OTN, unless the signals are carried through optical fibre.
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] Unlike SONET/SDH, OTN provides a mechanism to manage multiplexed wavelengths in a DWDM system.
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] OTN was designed to provide higher throughput (currently 400G) than its predecessor SONET/SDH, which stops at 40 Gbit/s, per channel.
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] ITU-T Recommendation G.709 is commonly called Optical Transport Network (OTN) (also called **digital wrapper technology** or **optical channel wrapper**).
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] As of December 2009, OTN has standardized the following line rates.
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] (LAN) PHY coming from IP/Ethernet switches and routers at full line rate (10.3 Gbit/s).
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] develop for transport of 10G LAN PHY, and one for 10G WAN PHY, over SDH and OTN.
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] The OTUk (k=1/2/2e/3/3e2/4) is an information structure into which another information structure called ODUk (k=1/2/2e/3/3e2/4) is mapped.
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] The ODUk signal is the server layer signal for client signals.
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] The OTN signals at all data-rates have the same frame structure but the frame period reduces as the data-rate increases.
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] As a result, the Time-Slot Interchange (TSI) technique of implementing SONET/SDH switch fabrics is not directly applicable to OTN switch fabrics.
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] OTN switch fabrics are typically implemented using Packet Switch Fabrics.
[src:dwdm/optical-transport-network] On a point-to-point OTN link there is latency due to forward error correction (FEC) processing.
[src:dwdm/reconfigurable-optical-add-drop-multiplexer] In optical communication, a **reconfigurable optical add-drop multiplexer** (**ROADM**) is a form of optical add-drop multiplexer that adds the ability to remotely switch traffic from a wavelength-division multiplexing (WDM) system at the wavelength layer.
[src:dwdm/reconfigurable-optical-add-drop-multiplexer] This is achieved through the use of a wavelength selective switching module.
[src:dwdm/reconfigurable-optical-add-drop-multiplexer] This allows individual or multiple wavelengths carrying data channels to be added and/or dropped from a transport fiber without the need to convert the signals on all of the WDM channels to electronic signals and back again to optical signals.
[src:dwdm/reconfigurable-optical-add-drop-multiplexer] The switching or reconfiguration functions of a ROADM can be achieved using a variety of switching technologies, including microelectromechanical systems (MEMS), liquid crystal, thermo optic and beam-steering switches in planar waveguide circuits, and tunable optical filter technology.
[src:dwdm/reconfigurable-optical-add-drop-multiplexer] MEMS and liquid crystal technologies are the most widely used.
[src:dwdm/reconfigurable-optical-add-drop-multiplexer] ROADMs were first introduced in 2002 with the introduction of DWDM.
[src:dwdm/reconfigurable-optical-add-drop-multiplexer] ROADMs can be directionless, colorless, contentionless, and gridless.
[src:dwdm/reconfigurable-optical-add-drop-multiplexer] Directionless means that any wavelength can be dropped from any fiber, and any wavelength or signal can be sent to any port in the ROADM.
[src:dwdm/reconfigurable-optical-add-drop-multiplexer] Colorless implies every port in the ROADM can handle or accept any wavelength or color of light.
[src:dwdm/reconfigurable-optical-add-drop-multiplexer] Contentionless means several identical wavelengths or signals can be dropped from several ports at the same time.
[src:dwdm/reconfigurable-optical-add-drop-multiplexer] Gridless means that the ROADM can handle frequencies or signals that aren't precisely 50 GHz apart from each other.
[src:dwdm/reconfigurable-optical-add-drop-multiplexer] This is relevant because 50 GHz spacing has been traditionally used in fiber optic communications.
[src:dwdm/wavelength-division-multiplexing] It essentially performs some relatively simple time-division multiplexing of lower-rate signals into a higher-rate carrier within the system (a common example is the ability to accept 4 OC-48s and then output a single OC-192 in the 1,550 nm band).
[src:dwdm/wavelength-division-multiplexing] In practice, the signal inputs and outputs will not be electrical but optical instead (typically at 1550 nm).
[src:dwdm/wavelength-division-multiplexing] A transponder can be made up of two transceivers placed after each other: the first transceiver converting the 1550 nm optical signal to/from an electrical signal, and the second transceiver converting the electrical signal to/from an optical signal at the required wavelength.
